abstract: >-
  An engineering log and benchmark suite documenting the practical envelope of running modern large language models (up to 70B
  parameters) on a consumer-grade dual AMD Radeon AI PRO R9700 32 GB workstation under ROCm 7.2 and vLLM 0.19. Version 0.2.0 introduces
  METHODOLOGY.md v1.0 — a single source of truth synthesizing Capitelli (2025) reporting schema, Kim et al. (2026) AI disclosure
  framework, Lerchner (2026) methodological humility, and ICMJE/COPE compliance — alongside universal Phase 1 envelope and Phase 2
  scaling sweep analyzers applicable to all 13 models in the suite. Phase 2 scaling sweep results for Qwen 3.6 27B BF16 (N=10..1000)
  yield three engineering findings under embargo classification: throughput knee occurs at approximately 8x the vLLM scheduler
  max_concurrency estimate (not at the estimate itself); the vLLM scheduler exhibits graceful degradation at 5x over the knee
  (-0.9% throughput) without starvation pathology; and the energy-optimal operating point in mWh per token differs from the
  throughput-optimal point, a trade-off invisible in marketing benchmarks reporting only peak aggregate tok/s. The version 0.1.0
  quantization-performance inversion finding (BF16 outpacing FP8 by approximately 75% on R9700) is reproduced and extended:
  KV-cache fp8_e4m3 produces a 5x slowdown vs default KV at this release, attributable to the absence of native FP8 KV kernels for
  gfx1201 in vLLM 0.19. Tier A statistical reruns (n=10 with Holm-Bonferroni FWER correction) are deferred to v0.2.1; current
  results are single-shot exploratory. Intended audience includes researchers preparing local AI infrastructure for privacy-sensitive
  workloads, hardware reviewers seeking reproducible methodology, and software maintainers working on RDNA 4 support in inference
  frameworks.
